================================================================
LEETCODE 3070 - Count Submatrices with Top-Left Element and Sum ≤ k
Difficulty: Medium
================================================================

QUESTION
--------
Given a 0-indexed integer matrix `grid` and an integer `k`,
return the number of submatrices that contain the top-left
element of the grid, and have a sum less than or equal to k.

Example 1:
  Input:  grid = [[7,6,3],[6,6,1]], k = 18
  Output: 4

Example 2:
  Input:  grid = [[7,2,9],[1,5,0],[2,6,6]], k = 20
  Output: 6

Constraints:
  - m == grid.length
  - n == grid[i].length
  - 1 <= n, m <= 1000
  - 0 <= grid[i][j] <= 1000
  - 1 <= k <= 10^9


APPROACH
--------
Key Insight:
  Every submatrix containing (0,0) is fully described by its
  bottom-right corner (i,j). So we just need to check whether
  the rectangle sum from (0,0) to (i,j) is <= k, for every cell.

Strategy: 2D Prefix Sum (built on the fly)
  - Scan the grid left-to-right, top-to-bottom
  - At each cell (i,j), compute prefix[i][j] using inclusion-exclusion:

      prefix[i][j] = grid[i][j]
                   + prefix[i-1][j]   (row above, same col)
                   + prefix[i][j-1]   (col left, same row)
                   - prefix[i-1][j-1] (top-left diagonal — subtracted
                                       because it was added twice above)

  - If prefix[i][j] <= k, increment count

Complexity:
  Time  -> O(m x n)  single pass over all cells
  Space -> O(m x n)  prefix sum table


DRY RUN
-------
Grid = [[7, 6, 3],    k = 18
        [6, 6, 1]]

Step-by-step prefix table build:

(i=0, j=0):
  prefix[0][0] = 7
  No row above, no col left.
  7 <= 18? YES  ->  count = 1

(i=0, j=1):
  prefix[0][1] = 6 + prefix[0][0](7) = 13
  No row above, so no diagonal subtraction.
  13 <= 18? YES  ->  count = 2

(i=0, j=2):
  prefix[0][2] = 3 + prefix[0][1](13) = 16
  16 <= 18? YES  ->  count = 3

(i=1, j=0):
  prefix[1][0] = 6 + prefix[0][0](7) = 13
  No col left, so no diagonal subtraction.
  13 <= 18? YES  ->  count = 4

(i=1, j=1):
  prefix[1][1] = 6 + prefix[0][1](13) + prefix[1][0](13) - prefix[0][0](7)
               = 6 + 13 + 13 - 7 = 25
  25 <= 18? NO   ->  count stays 4

(i=1, j=2):
  prefix[1][2] = 1 + prefix[0][2](16) + prefix[1][1](25) - prefix[0][1](13)
               = 1 + 16 + 25 - 13 = 29
  29 <= 18? NO   ->  count stays 4

Final prefix table:
  [  7, 13, 16 ]
  [ 13, 25, 29 ]

Answer: 4


SOLUTION (Java)
---------------
class Solution {
    public int countSubmatrices(int[][] grid, int k) {
        int rows = grid.length;
        int cols = grid[0].length;

        // prefix[i][j] = sum of rectangle from (0,0) to (i,j)
        int[][] prefix = new int[rows][cols];
        int count = 0;

        for (int i = 0; i < rows; i++) {
            for (int j = 0; j < cols; j++) {

                // Start with the cell's own value
                prefix[i][j] = grid[i][j];

                // Pull in the entire column above
                if (i > 0) prefix[i][j] += prefix[i-1][j];

                // Pull in the entire row to the left
                if (j > 0) prefix[i][j] += prefix[i][j-1];

                // Top-left rectangle was added twice above — subtract it once
                if (i > 0 && j > 0) prefix[i][j] -= prefix[i-1][j-1];

                // This cell is the bottom-right corner of one valid submatrix
                if (prefix[i][j] <= k) count++;
            }
        }

        return count;
    }
}

